h-voltage O $K$-edge feature at\n531 eV previously assigned to lattice O-redox processes could alternatively\narise from O-redox induced water intercalation and O-O dimer formation with\nlattice O at high states of charge. The O$_2$ surface loss route observed here\nconsists of 2 surface O$^{.-}$ radicals combining to form a peroxide ion, which\nis oxidised to O$_2$, leaving behind 2 O vacancies and 2 O$^{2-}$ ions:\neffectively 4 O$^{.-}$ radicals disproportionate to O$_2$ and 2 O$^{2-}$ ions.\nThe reaction liberates ca. 3 eV per O$_2$ molecule. Singlet oxygen formation is\ncaused by the singlet ground state of the peroxide ion, with spin conservation\ndictating the preferential release of $^1$O$_2$, the strongly exergonic\nreaction providing the free energy required for the formation of $^1$O$_2$ in\nits excited state.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 20 May 2022 23:40:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 14 Dec 2022 23:52:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-16"}
